Each layer includes the main artifacts that are involved into ensemble processing: (a) description
(parameters) Î of a single element related to the corresponding layer (state of the system (S) dataset
(D) or model (M)); (b) an ensemble {Î}, considered as a set of elements, described earlier; (c)
characteristics Ï† of the ensemble to assess the evaluated ensemble and make conclusions on the
ensemble analysis (one of the most important class of the ensemble characteristics is ensemble
diversity characteristics).
To process these artifacts we can define a set of operators to represent moving from one artifact to
another. The selected subset of these operators is described further. Each operator is defined by two
indices, denoting layer(s) and artifact(s) affected by the operator: Î“LA. These operators form a cycle
which is often considered as a basic ensemble analysis procedure within a single layer.
x

Î“*Î-{Î} (here and further * denotes any particular layer: S, D, M) defines ensemble creation
operator. Within the machine learning approach which usually applies Î“DÎ-{Î} operator (Dlayer) this operator represents diversity creation procedure [6]. Within statistical ensemble
collection this operator may refer to adding noise to initial data set or collecting various
stochastic diverse datasets [7]. Within statistical physics approach operator Î“SÎ-{Î} refers to
shifting from single state of the system to consideration of an ensemble of possible states.
Simulation ensemble is created using operator Î“MÎ-{Î} refers to collecting a set of models
which can be either the same models with different parameters [4], or different models [8].

